latestPosts.caption:
Beverly Hills, the herd awaits you. 

“Every category we humans use to communicate with one another is essential and art and scale are both powerful and impossible to ignore. These giant, beautiful beings touring the world speak louder and more profoundly than any orator or activist can possibly be. 

Their texture speaks of their home territories, they speak of the Indigenous communities who are the guardians of so many wild areas that are left on earth today. It’s my firm belief that we are long past the time when electing to abdicate our futures is a choice. Sitting on the sidelines and wringing our hands is not action nor is it acceptable.

No matter where you are, what you do, there is a role for you to step up to the long front of people around the world who choose health, beauty and life - this is the message the March of the Great Elephants brings to us so clearly.” - @kristine_tompkins

🐘🌸

Making this finale extra fragrant is world leading perfumer @xerjoff who created CoExistence, a special #SpraytoHelp perfume inspired by the flowers found in Asian elephant habitats. Each gorgeous hand painted bottle supports the herd’s coexistence mission.

📷 Elisa Ferrari

latestPosts.caption:
A fragrant finish line in Beverly Hills @xerjoff 🐘✨

They have crossed oceans, highways, beaches and endless plains. Walked clifftops & cobblestones through sand and snow. Made millions of friends and spoken for all animals great and small.

Their migration speaks for the millions of wild animals navigating plantations, highways, and urban spaces around the world through their story from India where they live alongside their creators, @therealeleco, who live alongside their real life counterparts and know them as extended family.

To the Matriarchs, Tuskers, the mighty movers, shakers, lifters, loaders, cheerleaders, and champions who helped carry this herd from east to west coast; and to @xerjoff who have been behind them from the very first step, the herd salutes you and your heroic support.

Their epic final journey was powered by @chantecaille, who have backed conservation efforts in every continent for the last 20 years and @hertz, the ultimate travel partner for wild adventures and great big summer roadtrips.

Their migration is now complete, but the elephants still have a remarkable story to tell - come and listen in Beverly Gardens Park from July 1 - August 1.

Finish line event generously supported by: @chappellet_winery @thelostexplorer and hosted by the wonderful @thewallisbh 💖

latestPosts.caption:
When photographer @stevewinterphoto captured the cougar P-22 beneath the Hollywood sign, the image ignited public imagination, catalyzed a global movement, and helped make the impossible possible: the world’s largest wildlife crossing, now under construction in Los Angeles.

This incredible story is about connection and people like conservationist @yosemitebethy (Beth Pratt) who helped turn heartbreak into hope. It’s also about how a big cat’s spirit lives on and is now embodied in the surreal sight of a herd of life-sized elephants standing in the heart of LA, thanks to the brilliant people at @greatelephantmigration!

Hand-woven by Indigenous artists @therealeleco in India from lantana camara, an invasive plant transformed into art, these sculptures carry with them the soul of the real elephants they represent. Their presence is a reminder of something larger: that healing is possible. That bridges, literal and symbolic, can be built when people come together.

From India to Kenya, from Blackfeet Nation to California, these elephants have become powerful messengers of coexistence. And now, standing on a bridge meant to reconnect wild lands and restore lost pathways, they remind us what’s possible when we move with courage, creativity, and compassion. Love and gratitude to the extraordinary people at @greatelephantmigration @therealeleco @fourpaws.usa @indigenous_led @lionguardians_ @chantecaille @hertz @annenbergarts

latestPosts.caption:
After thousands of miles on the road across deserts, mountains, cities, and coastlines, the herd of 100 life-size elephants has reached Los Angeles. Each of these elephants from @greatelephantmigration carries a story  of coexistence, of craft, of climate resilience,and of hope.

Born in the Nilgiri Hills of southern India, these elephants were created by @THEREALELECO. Over 200 Indigenous artisans from the Bettakurumba, Paniya, Kattunayakan, and Soliga communities. For five years, they hand-built each elephant from lantana camara, one of the world’s most destructive invasive weeds. This fast-growing shrub is choking India’s forests, pushing animals into human spaces and escalating conflict. But in these artisans’ hands, a threat became a symbol  of healing.

These elephants are modeled on real, wild individuals that roam India’s forests, many of them outside protected areas. In India, humans and elephants share land, water, and food. It’s one of the world’s greatest conservation miracles: in the past 30 years, even as India’s human population doubled to 1.4 billion, the populations of elephants, rhinos, lions, and tigers also grew.

This is possible because coexistence is not an idea.It’s a lived practice and the result is a rare kind of empathy that guides both policy and daily life.

The Great Elephant Migration celebrates this wisdom. Each step these elephants took across the U.S. was a moving call for the world to reimagine its relationship with nature. This past week, we traveled from the red rocks of Zion to the streets of Las Vegas and finally Los Angeles. Now, they stand in Beverly Hills, unexpected, majestic, and very much alive. Each elephant is available for adoption, with proceeds going directly to projects that support human-wildlife coexistence and restore biodiversity, both in the U.S. and around the world.

The entire journey has been made carbon neutral, from creation to transport, thanks to a large-scale biochar initiative in India that turns invasive lantana into carbon-sequestering soil. By the end of 2025, over 2,600 tons of carbon will be removed from the atmosphere through this effort.  Enormous gratitude @hertz @chantecaille

latestPosts.caption:
100 elephants. 5,000 miles. 13 months. One EXTRAORDINARY migration!!!!

This past week, @greatelephantmigration stood among cliffs and canyons, deserts and silence, listening to stories around fires and beneath stars. From the Blackfeet to the Maasai to the Adivasi, each voice carried the same truth: people and animals don’t have to live in conflict. Coexistence is not a dream, it’s a practice that begins with empathy and endures through understanding.

Elephants are a flagship species and their migration speaks for the millions of other wild animals navigating highways and urban spaces around the world. These elephants are storytellers in motion, carrying the voices of real elephants in India, who navigate dense human landscapes daily, and the wisdom of Indigenous communities who’ve long known that conservation isn’t about control. It’s about care. 
 They have crossed oceans, highways, beaches and wild plains, from coast to coast, to help us understand the need and possibility, for peaceful coexistence.

As they travel, they are raising millions to power human-wildlife coexistence through the sale of sculptures. @THEREALELECO created each elephant to represent a real elephant living alongside communities. Now, after 5,000 miles and 13 months on the road, the migration is complete. 100 elephants born of art, story, and hope have arrived in Los Angeles. The herd has arrived but the journey is far from over!!

Walk among them at the Wallis Annenberg Center for the Performing Arts in Beverly Hills Garden Park from July 1 to August 1 and be part of the next chapter in this story of coexistence. 

To the Matriarchs, Tuskers, and every mighty mover, shaker, lifter, loader, cheerleader, and champion who helped carry this herd from east to west coast and to so many friends, you carried more than sculptures, you created and carried a movement. Enormous gratitude and love to all the people and partnerships. @therealeleco @fourpaws.usa @indigenous_led @lionguardians_ @chantecaille @hertz @annenbergarts

latestPosts.caption:
Right now, as the sun rises in the Grand Tetons something completely surreal is happening. There’s a herd of elephants standing just outside the National Museum of Wildlife Art in Jackson Hole. And I know... elephants in Wyoming?! It’s not something I ever expected to see but it’s also kind of magical.

These aren’t live animals, but they carry so much life. Each one is a hand-crafted, life-sized sculpture made by Indigenous artists in India, part of @GreatElephantMigration, a movement to bring awareness to how humans and elephants can live together peacefully. They’re traveling across the U.S., stopping in iconic landscapes from coast to coast, and this week, they’re here. And I’m here with them.

Being this close to them in the open air, seeing the way their shadows of their trunks stretch out across the grass in this light honestly reminds me of moments in Africa. That feeling when the elephants appear on the horizon, quietly and powerfully claiming their space. It gives me chills every time.

As an honorary “Matriarch” of this herd (still pinching myself about that), I’ve been lucky to follow their journey and tell some of the real stories behind these sculptures. One that stays with me is Madhubala, an African elephant who spent years in heartbreaking isolation in the Karachi Zoo. She lived a sad and solitary life until @FOURPAWS.INTERNATIONAL stepped in and gave her a second chance, a chance to be an elephant again.

Now, she’s part of this symbolic herd and we’re traveling together, from Jackson Hole to Los Angeles, sharing a message of resilience, empathy, and hope along the way.

I’m incredibly grateful to be here, to learn and witness and to share powerful messages of hope.  No wild animal should live in captivity except, maybe, in the heart.

#EmpathyForElephants #FollowMadhubala @WILDLIFEARTJH @FOURPAWS.USA

latestPosts.caption:
📍Browning, MT - 1,700 miles to the finish line…

A new frontier in conservation dawns. Indigenous Peoples have always practised coexistence with the natural world. Over the last few days, the creators of the herd @therealeleco have been reunited with their elephants for the first time since they waved them farewell one year ago, when this adventure began. They gathered in Montana, with members of the Blackfeet community and our Maasai friends from Kenya, in a powerful moment of cultural exchange around the herd, marking an evolution of thought and approach in wildlife conservation efforts globally. Thank you @indigenous_led @lionguardians_ for sharing your stories with us 🐘🦬🦁

Next stop, @wildlifeartjh, Jackson Hole, to reunite with the rest of the herd and The Matriarchy.

The drums are beating, and the road is calling.

Elephant moving machines generously provided  @hertz 💛

latestPosts.caption:
Elephants, Buffalo & Matriarchs…

Just one week ago, the herd were deeply honoured to be a part of Blackfeet Nation’s 5th annual Iinnii Days, a special cultural gathering that honours buffalo. We are grateful to the Blackfeet community for welcoming the elephants during this beautiful 4-day event.

Now, in just a few days, they begin their FINAL journey to the finishing line. To mark this momentous leg, for the very first time, the exceptional Adivasi artisans from @therealeleco will join their pachyderm creations and migrate with them all the way from Montana to Beverly Hills, through America’s most iconic landscapes.

They’ll be joined by lion-loving Maasai Warriors from Kenya and members of Blackfeet Nation, supported by our NGO partners @lionguardians and @indigenousled. These communities have long lived in deep relationship with animals. As they migrate beside the elephants, they’ll help share an ancient knowledge of coexistence that these elephants embody.

This final stretch will also unfold in matriarchal fashion—YES! Led by a convoy of powerhouse women driving each member of the herd, championing coexistence between people and animals from all corners of the world:

📸 @amivitale 
🦦 @kristine_tompkins 
🐺 @miacanestrini
🦁 @gretafrancescaiori 
🦬 Cristina Mormorunni
🌍 @ecoedith 

They’re sending GOOD VIBRATIONS and subsonic rumbles of deepest gratitude to the partners who’ve made this epic journey possible:

⭐️ Matriarchal Migration supported by: @chantecaille
🚚 Migrating Machines provided by: @hertz
🏕️ Accommodation Partners: @calderahouse @fsjacksonhole @undercanvasofficial @autocamp 
Logistics gymnasts: @ibi_international_logistics @seko_logistics 
Migration merchandise: @lovebrandco 

The countdown begins…

A Blackfeet Blessing ❤️🐘

With arrival in each stop of the migration, we take a moment to honor the herd. In Jackson Hole, this celebration was extra special.

In a beautiful meeting of worlds, Blackfeet artist Terrance Guardipee led the ceremony, weaving together Blackfeet traditions with those from the Nilgiri Hills—both rooted in reverence for the natural world and all the beings who share it. A thousand elephant trumpets ring out in gratitude to Terrance, the Jackson community, and the National Museum of Wildlife Art @wildlifeartjh, who wished the elephants love and luck last week. 

Meanwhile, the rest of the herd have made it to Blackfeet lands in Browning, MT, where this week they joined the annual Iinnii Days celebration with @indigenous_led, honoring their buffalo cousins. Meet the Browning herd through June 16, and the Jackson Hole herd through June 20. ❤️

📷 Photos by Madison Webb, courtesy of the National Museum of Wildlife Art
